## Read Before Acting

These files are the minimum context for acting correctly in this project.
Read them in order. They are tool-neutral; the same files are used by
Codex, Claude Code, LM Studio, and any other adapter.

- `core/principles/development-principles.md` — development principles that apply to all projects.
- `core/rules/token-efficiency.md` — token discipline rules; apply them to every model turn.
- `core/rules/maintainability.md` — the six maintainability dimensions; required for every code change.
- `core/rules/model-routing.md` — routing decisions between local and cloud model tiers.
- `PROJECT_CONTEXT.md` — compact, durable context for this project specifically.
- `CODEMAP.md` — file and module map; use it to locate code before scanning the repo.
- `VERIFY.md` — verification commands; run these after every change.

If `PROJECT_CONTEXT.md`, `CODEMAP.md`, or `VERIFY.md` do not yet exist in
this project, create them first using the templates in
`core/templates/` from your SustainDev checkout. Do not start coding
in a project that lacks the project layer — the token-efficiency
guarantees depend on it.

## Token Efficiency (Cursor-specific notes)

Cursor's @-references (`@file`, `@folder`, `@docs`) are the cheapest way
to bring context into a turn. Prefer them over copy-paste and over broad
"explore the repo" prompts. Reference `CODEMAP.md` first; only widen
scope when CODEMAP plus the named file is insufficient.

When a task is large or vague, do **not** ask Cursor to plan and execute
in one turn. Capture the idea using SustainDev's `capture-idea.sh`,
prepare it with `prepare-task.py` (local model), then hand the prepared
brief back to Cursor for execution. The local-tier prework prevents
30k-token cloud-model warmups on context the local model can produce
for free.

## Verification Commands

Verification commands are in `VERIFY.md`. Run the full sequence after
every code change before reporting the task complete. If a verification
command is missing or stale, update `VERIFY.md` as part of the change.

## AI Policy

Actions permitted and restricted for AI tools working in this project
are in `AI_POLICY.md`. Read it before taking any action that writes
files, runs commands, or calls external services. Cursor's Agent mode
is bound by this policy the same as any other tool — the file is
tool-neutral by design.

## Maintainability Constraints

Project-specific maintainability rules that extend the core six
dimensions are in `MAINTAINABILITY_NOTES.md`. The six dimensions in
`core/rules/maintainability.md` (architecture fit, coupling, naming,
testability, error handling, change cost) still apply unchanged;
`MAINTAINABILITY_NOTES.md` adds project-specific constraints on top.

Every code change must justify its impact on each of the six
dimensions, even if briefly. "No impact" is a valid answer; silence
is not.

## Skills Available

- `core/skills/idea-to-prepared-task/SKILL.md` — captures a vague idea
  and produces a structured task brief queued for execution. The hero
  workflow for v0.1; use it whenever a request is larger than a few
  lines or touches files Cursor has not seen this session.

## Decisions and Risks

- `DECISIONS.md` records architectural decisions with rationale.
  Check before proposing something that has already been considered.
- `RISKS.md` lists active risks and their mitigations. Read before
  changing code near a known risk area.
